    "created_at": "2013-11-06T00:45:11Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-11-06T00:45:11Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "There are a couple of issues with the current design (I take all the\nblame!) and its extensions to multiple buttons or even per-notebook\ndropdown menu:\n- It is bad visual design to have elements that are repeated needlessly. It\n  makes the design much more busy, distracts and confuses the user visually.\n  Simple is almost always better visually. Putting a dropdown menu for each\n  notebook with different actions is better than a bunch of separate buttons,\n  but you still have the repeated dropdown menus. The only way I would even\n  consider a per-notebook dropdown is that if it only shows on hover.\n- Having buttons/UI for each Notebook that are right justified in the list\n  item makes for a difficult user experience when the window is wide. More\n  than once, I have clicked on the \"Delete\" button for the wrong notebook.\n- Multiple selection actions are an important abstraction that I think we\n  do need to support in the notebook list. If we want to support this, it\n  would be confusing to also support Notebook specific buttons/dropdowns.\n- It is easy to build nice keyboard bindings for a checkbox driven UI like\n  gmail. More difficult for per-item buttons.\n- Over time we will add more and more actions, making the per-notebook UI\n  even more difficult to scale.\n\nCheers, Brian\n\nOn Mon, Nov 4, 2013 at 11:38 PM, Matthias Bussonnier <\nnotifications@github.com> wrote:\n\n> I tend to agree with @Zsailer https://github.com/Zsailer, I was\n> pissed-off when google removed the common action on every mail.\n> I understand that some action are good on multiple selections, but some\n> are inherently 1-notebook action.\n> \n> —\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHubhttps://github.com/ipython/ipython/pull/4467#issuecomment-27752444\n> .\n\n## \n\nBrian E. Granger\nCal Poly State University, San Luis Obispo\nbgranger@calpoly.edu and ellisonbg@gmail.com\n"
  },
